Answer:
1. CORE RULE:
When a pupil actively discloses abuse, staff must listen, reassure, inform the pupil that the information will be passed on, and then verbally report to the Designated Safeguarding Lead (DSL) [1.13]. When staff only suspect abuse based on indicators, they must report any concerns to the DSL without investigating [1.11.L21].

2. EXCEPTIONS AND CONDITIONS:
*   However, if the school believes that notifying parents could increase the risk to the child or exacerbate the problem, advice will be sought first from Children's Social Care [1.13].

3. FINAL ANSWER:
The school's response differs based on whether a student actively discloses abuse or if staff only suspect it. When a pupil actively discloses abuse, the staff member's response involves a direct interaction where they allow the pupil to speak freely, remain calm, offer comfort, avoid investigative questions (though clarifying questions are permissible), and at an appropriate time, inform the pupil that the information must be passed on [1.13]. The staff member then reports verbally to the Designated Safeguarding Lead (DSL) and informs the pupil of the next steps [1.13]. In contrast, when staff only suspect abuse based on indicators, their responsibility is to report *any* concerns to the DSL, regardless of how minor or insignificant they may seem, and they are explicitly told not to investigate or decide whether a child has been abused [1.11.L21]. In both situations (disclosure or suspicion), the DSL will normally contact parents, unless notifying parents could increase the risk to the child or exacerbate the problem, in which case advice will be sought from Children's Social Care first [1.13].

